{
  "text": "The capacity of the different cell types to adhere to fibronectin-coated substrates was quantified using the cell spreading assay described in detail previously [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Although the results were qualitatively similar using the standard adhesion buffer or serum-free NCTC 135 medium, a higher percentage of each cell type tended to adhere in the serum-free medium; consequently, most of the assays were performed in the latter. Briefly, the wells of cluster dishes (6 \u00d7 35-ram from Costar, Cambridge, MA) were pre-coated with the indicated concentrations of purified human plasma fibronectin for 1 h; then nonspecific attachment sites were blocked by incubation for 30 min with 10 mg/ml of heat-denatured bovine serum albumin. Cells were detached mechanically from the substrate of normal cultures as for normal passage, centrifuged, and transferred to fresh serum-free medium, and then replated into the fibronectin-coated wells. After 2 h at 37\"C, the cultures were fixed with glutaraldehyde and scored for percentage of spread cells as previously described [CITATION_3] , counting a total of 600 cells in random fields per point and calculating the mean and standard error. ",
  "citation_candidates": [
